Collins Place (far side of house not shown.) west side, north from Northern Boulevard, (right not shown). The side shown faces on Lawrence St. This is a set of three views of the L. B. Prince residence of 1873. Views two and three show an offspring of the original Cedar of Lebanon. The Prince family maintained an extensive nursery known through the world. Collins Place, (right, not shown) west side, north from Northern Boulevard (foreground of View No. 4), showing the Embre House later the Prince house. The original house almost directly opposite the present one was razed in 1863. Duke of Clarence, the later William IV was a guest here. See other views for more data.

Collins Place, west side, north from Northern Boulevard (foreground), showing the Embre house in a set of three views. This place was erected about 1780. William Robert Prince purchased it in 1827 after his marriage in 1826 to Charlotte G. Collins, daughter of Gov. Chas. Collins of Rhode Island. His son Le Baron Bradford Prince, at one time Governor of New Mexico, was born in 1840 and died in 1922. To the right of the barn in the foreground (not shown) was the Main Street Station of the Long Island Railroad, Whitestone Branch.
